Here is a simple batch script that will go through each directory and sub-directory, check if there are any audio files and if not, it checks if the directory is empty. If it passes these criteria, it will add the directory to a txt file.

```batch
@echo off
setlocal enabledelayedexpansion

:: List of audio file extensions
set "audioExts=.mp3 .m4a .flac .opus .wav"

:: Output file name
set "outputFile=nonAudioDirs.txt"

:: Delete output file from previous runs
if exist "%~dp0%outputFile%" del "%~dp0%outputFile%"

:: Scan directories
for /r /d %%D in (*) do (
    set "hasAudio=0"
    for %%F in (%%D\*) do (
        for %%E in (%audioExts%) do (
            if "%%~xF"=="%%E" (
                set "hasAudio=1"
                goto :NextDir
            )
        )
    )
    if !hasAudio! equ 0 (
        if not exist "%%D\*" (
            echo %%D>>"%~dp0%outputFile%"
        )
    )
    :NextDir
)

echo Done!
pause
```

Remember to save this with a `.bat` or `.cmd` extension. Double-clicking the saved file will run the script and create a text file in the same directory, listing all the paths to directories that contain only non-audio files or no files at all.

Please note that this script might take some time to execute if there are a lot of subdirectories or files to check.

